source: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipes/prosciutto-eggs-benedict-648884650b7af205da01b334
time required: 20 minutes
cuisine: North America
servings: 2
---

Wash and dry produce.

Dice @tomato{1} into ½-inch pieces. Halve and toast @brioche buns{2}.

In a #large bowl{}, combine half the @balsamic vinegar{2%teaspoon}, half the @Dijon mustard{1%teaspoon}, 1 TBSP @olive oil{1%tablespoon}, and @sugar{1/2%teaspoon} (all the vinegar, 2 TBSP olive oil, and 1 tsp sugar for 4 servings). Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

In a #small pot{}, combine @cream sauce base{4%ounce}, @cream cheese{4%tablespoon}, and remaining @Dijon mustard{1%teaspoon} over medium heat. Cook, whisking, until smooth and thickened, ~{2-4%minutes}.

Taste and season with a pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{} if needed. Remove pot from heat; cover to keep warm.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%teaspoon} in a #large pan{}, preferably #nonstick pan{} over medium heat. Once hot, crack @eggs{4} into pan and cover. (For 4 servings, you may want to cook eggs in batches.) Fry eggs to preference. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

While eggs cook, add @mixed greens{2%ounce} and tomato to bowl with dressing. Toss to coat.

Divide toasted buns, cut sides up, between plates; top each bun half with a folded @prosciutto{2%ounce} slice, an egg, and sauce.

Serve eggs Benedict with salad on the side.

> Wash hands and surfaces after handling raw eggs. Consuming raw or undercooked eggs may increase your risk of foodborne illness.